= Chapter 1: The Sparks of Luminos-Vara
\
The deep underground did not know the sun, but it was far from dark.

High above the cobblestone streets, massive arches of polished deepslate held up the ceiling of the world. Hanging from those arches were hundreds of iron lanterns, each burning with a brilliant, dancing blue flame. This was soul fire, and its gentle cerulean glow touched everything in the grand city of Luminos-Vara.

Down on the walkways, the city was alive with the sound of footsteps and bright conversation. A tall citizen with a heavy brow and a dark coat—an artisan—waved politely to a neighbor in a simple brown robe who was carrying a stack of leather-bound books toward the grand library. Here, there were no divides. There were no factions. They were simply the people of the blue light, and their city was a paradise for the greatest minds in the Overworld.

Through the crowd rushed Valen.

Valen was a young apprentice, barely old enough to carry his own heavy toolbox, but his eyes were always wide with curiosity. His fingers were permanently stained with dark ink and charcoal from drawing blueprints, and his leather apron jingled with loose redstone dust, iron springs, and bits of flint.

"Watch your step, young one!" a metalworker called out with a laugh as Valen ducked under a long bronze pipe being carried into a workshop.

"Sorry! Late for a calibration!" Valen squeaked, dodging a stack of glowing glow-berry crates just arrived from the lower farm caverns.

He turned a sharp corner and ducked into his favorite place in the entire world: the Central Innovation Courtyard.

In the center of the courtyard stood a massive, towering creation. It was a giant automaton built from heavy deepslate, smooth stone, and reinforced iron joints. It stood nearly four blocks tall, with a broad, faceless head and two long, powerful arms resting at its sides. It was a Warden—the ultimate protector. Right now, it was completely still, a beautiful monument to the city’s engineering. Built to guard the deep tunnels from monsters, it was perfectly clean, its gray stone skin gleaming under the blue lantern light.

Valen paused for just a second to admire it. One day, he thought, my inventions will be as grand as the Wardens.

He rushed past the giant protector and hurried down a flight of stairs into his private workshop. The room smelled of sulfur, dried kelp, and melted wax. Tables were cluttered with obsidian blocks, buckets of lava, and strange piles of glowing soul sand brought back from dangerous expeditions to the Nether.

For months, Luminos-Vara’s inventors had used Nether portals to gather soul sand to keep the city's lights burning. But Valen wanted more. He didn't want to just visit the fiery wastes of the Nether. He wanted to know if there were other worlds out there.

"The resonance is the key," Valen muttered to himself, pulling a heavy lever on his workbench.

In the center of his room stood a rectangular frame. It wasn't made of obsidian like a Nether portal. Instead, Valen had meticulously carved blocks of reinforced deepslate, lining the inner edge with a delicate mixture of crushed redstone and compressed soul sand. He believed that if he could find the right frequency—the right vibration—the frame would tear open a door to somewhere entirely new.

He picked up a heavy iron hammer and a tuning fork made of pure gold.

"Test forty-seven," Valen whispered, his heart hammering against his ribs.

He struck the golden tuning fork. A sharp, clear PING rang out through the silent workshop. Instantly, Valen pressed the vibrating fork against the bottom corner of the deepslate frame.

The redstone dust along the frame began to hiss. The blue soul sand caught fire, but it didn't burn with a normal flame. The fire stretched, turning into a deep, swirling vortex of dark violet and midnight blue. The air in the room grew suddenly cold, and a strange, heavy wind began to pull at Valen’s apron.

The frame vibrated violently. The sound changed from a high-pitched ring to a deep, echoing thrum that vibrated right through the stone floor and into Valen's boots.

Through the swirling blue energy of the portal, Valen couldn't see the Nether. There was no lava, no red netherrack. Instead, he caught a glimpse of massive, towering shapes made of a strange, pitch-black material. And growing along the edges of that distant world were beautiful, crystalline shards that pulsed with a faint, mesmerizing light.

Valen gasped, taking a step closer, his eyes reflecting the dark blue void.

"I did it," he breathed into the quiet room. "A new world."

He didn't know it yet, but far away, on the other side of that fresh doorway, something ancient and trapped had just opened its eyes.